
AST environment construction turns sorted declaration shells into semantic frontend state.

This is where type identity becomes real.
Headers provide shape and order.
AST resolves meaning.

## Main paths

- `src/compiler_frontend/ast/module_ast/environment/`
- `src/compiler_frontend/ast/type_resolution/`
- `src/compiler_frontend/ast/module_ast/environment/public_surface.rs`
- `src/compiler_frontend/datatypes/`

## Environment construction

`build_ast_environment` consumes header-built file visibility, then resolves:

- declaration metadata
- compile-time constants
- nominal structs
- choices
- function signatures
- receiver catalog data
- trait metadata
- shared environment side channels

AST resolves declaration shells in sorted order.
It may register nominal identity and generic parameter metadata before constants so constructors are name-resolvable.
Field and variant constructor shells stay unresolved until their semantic `TypeId`s can be checked and written to `TypeEnvironment`.

## Type resolution

`type_resolution/` owns parsed type-reference resolution to canonical `TypeId`.

It handles:

- source-visible lookup
- type aliases
- builtin types
- options
- growable collections
- fixed-capacity collections
- hashmaps
- generic parameters
- concrete generic nominal instantiation
- external package types that have frontend mappings

Fixed capacity is type identity.
`{Int}` and `{4 Int}` are different semantic types.
Maps are their own constructed shape.
They are not collection variants.

## Visibility through ScopeContext

AST consumes the header-built file visibility environment through `ScopeContext`.
It can validate semantic use of visible symbols, but it must not rebuild import bindings or rediscover top-level visibility.

Expression and type resolution should use the active `ScopeContext`, not global bare-name lookup.

All user-visible names go through one collision policy.
Same-file declarations, source imports, external imports, type aliases, prelude symbols and builtins can't silently shadow each other.

## Public module API validation

`module_ast/environment/public_surface.rs` owns semantic public module API validation after type and trait identities are resolved.

Public module APIs must not expose private root-only types in:

- signatures
- fields
- aliases
- generic bounds
- exported constant types
- exported trait metadata

Receiver methods are visible across a module boundary when the root `export:` block exposes the receiver type's source surface.
Type aliases in the root don't automatically re-export private implementation methods.

## TypeEnvironment boundary

`TypeEnvironment` is the canonical module-local source of semantic type identity.
`TypeId` equality in the active environment is the only semantic comparison rule.

Function signatures store canonical `TypeId`s on `ReturnSlot` and `Declaration` after resolution.
Parallel `DataType` values remain available for diagnostics only.

AST body emission receives `AstTypeInterner`, a narrow facade over `TypeEnvironment`.
It allows derived type interning and module-local compatibility caching without permitting nominal declaration mutation.

## Member lookup

`TypeEnvironment` member queries expose borrowed field/variant views and direct member lookup helpers.
AST, HIR and backend-facing lowering should use those semantic views instead of cloning member lists for lookup.

Source fields, receiver calls and compiler-owned collection/map builtin member access live under `field_access/`.

## Public API drift hazards

Be strict here.
Subtle type-resolution drift spreads everywhere.

Common mistakes:

- using `DataType` for semantic comparisons
- resolving names through global maps instead of `ScopeContext`
- rebuilding import visibility in AST
- cloning member lists for lookup instead of using semantic views
- leaking private root-only types through public API surfaces
- treating receiver methods as independently importable symbols
- resolving fixed collection capacity as a backend allocation hint
- modelling maps as collection capacity variants

